04444nmm a2200637Ia 9781501703898DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20162016nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979882442  a97815017038987 a10.7591/97815017038982doi  a(DE-B1597)480048  a(OCoLC)946725850  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY0481pa370qDE-1011 aLee, Elizabeth M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aClass and Campus Life :bManaging and Experiencing Inequality at an Elite College /cElizabeth M. Lee. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (280 p.) :b1 table  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 2015, the New York Times reported, "The bright children of janitors and nail salon workers, bus drivers and fast-food cooks may not have grown up with the edifying vacations, museum excursions, daily doses of NPR and prep schools that groom Ivy applicants, but they are coveted candidates for elite campuses." What happens to academically talented but economically challenged "first-gen" students when they arrive on campus? Class markers aren’t always visible from a distance, but socioeconomic differences permeate campus life—and the inner experiences of students—in real and sometimes unexpected ways. In Class and Campus Life, Elizabeth M. Lee shows how class differences are enacted and negotiated by students, faculty, and administrators at an elite liberal arts college for women located in the Northeast. Using material from two years of fieldwork and more than 140 interviews with students, faculty, administrators, and alumnae at the pseudonymous Linden College, Lee adds depth to our understanding of inequality in higher education. An essential part of her analysis is to illuminate the ways in which the students’ and the college’s practices interact, rather than evaluating them separately, as seemingly unrelated spheres. She also analyzes underlying moral judgments brought to light through cultural connotations of merit, hard work by individuals, and making it on your own that permeate American higher education. Using students’ own descriptions and understandings of their experiences to illustrate the complexity of these issues, Lee shows how the lived experience of socioeconomic difference is often defined in moral, as well as economic, terms, and that tensions, often unspoken, undermine students’ senses of belonging.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aClass consciousnesszUnited States. 0aCollege environmentzUnited States. 0aEducational sociologyzUnited StatesvCross-cultural studies. 0aElite (Social sciences)xEducation (Higher)zUnited States. 0aIntercultural communicationzUnited States. 0aStudents with social disabilitiesxEducation (Higher)zUnited States. 0aWomen college studentszUnited StatesxSocial conditions. 0aWomen's collegeszUnited States. 4aEducation & History Of Education. 4aSociology & Social Science.  aSocial class, campus, inequality, higher education, classism, college.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066749340uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150170389840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501703898423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501703898/original  a978-3-11-066749-3  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles